{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1783156136,"nonce":"PlGcSjstkinHvZtvSmWhcTj8N5M=","message":"Done — shipped in PR #75 (squash bc5a9e4). SQLite now introspects table CHECK constraints and column collations by parsing the stored CREATE TABLE text (a paren/quote/comment-aware body splitter factored from the existing keyword tokenizer), drops the renderer rejections, and renders both. A CHECK has no round-tripping name, so a new defaulted core seam SchemaIntrospect::canonical_check_name derives its name from the (trimmed) expression on both sides (PG/MySQL keep the default); collations render quoted via write_quoted_ident and round-trip. A collated column adds natively (ALTER TABLE ADD COLUMN COLLATE); a CHECK/collation change rebuilds. Codex review: 4 rounds, all real P2s fixed with regression tests (drop of check validation/enforcement metadata; unquoted collation name; mid-UTF-8 panic on a non-ASCII unquoted identifier), ending clean. Note: an equivalent but differently-spelled external CHECK/collation, or an unregistered custom collation at CREATE time, are documented limitations (matches the recover-exactly-what-the-renderer-wrote approach).","files":null}]}